title: Approaches to Learning: Preschool Domain
subject: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework (2015-)

document.title: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework Ages Birth to Five

2352C7E1C49348169CB53AF1EEF2A5D8.description:
Uses objects or materials to represent
something else during play, such as
using a paper plate or Frisbee as a
steering wheel.

102EDB698E4F4EE9A6798457C160FB35.description:
Uses imagination with materials to
create stories or works of art.

C8EEDF3737A14482BC75B2B7013D4561.description: Engages in social and pretend play.

C59E078B290B48908ADC5C396843D88C.description:
48 to 60 Months: Develops more elaborate imaginary
play, stories, and other creative works
with children and adults.

D6883D92F30244D2A82AB0A8DFBC8EA7.description:
36 to 48 Months: Consistently uses imagination in play
and other creative works. Begins to
communicate creative ideas to other
children and adults.

D383EF33DFDA4DE785636688CB64DA0E.description: Child uses imagination in play and interactions with others.

0B7DCE8032FB4AC6A190BE0E9C73A9F6.description:
Uses multiple means of communication
to creatively express thoughts, feelings,
or ideas.

D882551666244E5EA3490E76A9B5DB7E.description:
Approaches tasks, activities, and play
in ways that show creative problem
solving.

3A1AA051B1E4492194287FEEECFA6DA5.description:
Asks questions related to tasks or
activities that indicate thinking about
new ways to accomplish the task or
activity.

48219E8F00284ECEAED81E3172977A61.description:
48 to 60 Months: Communicates creative ideas and
actions both with and without
prompting from adults.

C4482FD1B54C4F098C23653796A85017.description:
36 to 48 Months: Responds to adults’ prompts to express
creative ideas in words and/or actions.

A8612A39A84A418FAE39D72C46927661.description: Child expresses creativity in thinking and communication.

7C1ED5CBEFDE4F3A991F46F7439D71FD.description:
Demonstrates eagerness to learn about
and discuss a range of topics, ideas, and
activities.

A41FC31B480B490F9DD8E47BF8CEBB33.description:
Is willing to participate in new activities
or experiences even if they are
perceived as challenging.

5504FB55CED94E9A8FF6D40C27306A07.description:
Asks questions and seeks new
information.

A0FECA16B74C429EB639BF584A2F2AD9.description:
48 to 60 Months: Seeks out new information and
explores new play and tasks both
independently and with adult support.

A8DED2B07A6349CF843BDB4CDDA9B23F.description:
36 to 48 Months: Seeks out new information and explores
new play and tasks with adult support.

B278E8770CFF4015A6C5B4A001C1F0E9.description: Child shows interest in and curiosity about the world around them.

BF92671A317F456A9BA9E36B1AF9C9F0.description:
Plans play scenarios, such as dramatic
play or construction, by establishing
roles for play, using appropriate
materials, and generating appropriate
scenarios to be enacted.

E39DA570B7554A33A5A7B4372137887B.description:
Independently identifies and seeks
things to complete activities or tasks,
such as gathering art supplies to make
a mask or gathering cards to play a
matching activity.

9497EA2E75BB4EFEAB4F729EF351911B.description:
Makes choices and communicates these
to adults and other children.

652FACA8D996468290A73C4D9088FB34.description:
48 to 60 Months: Frequently shows initiative, particularly
when engaged in preferred activities.
Demonstrates a willingness and
capability to work independently for
increasing amounts of time.

72D145158E39429EB171EA3D6EFB27CA.description:
36 to 48 Months: Regularly shows initiative, particularly
in interactions with familiar adults.
Works independently for brief periods
of time without adult prompting.

F40474BA86F04DCC8DF77A20D96A153D.description:
Transitions between activities without
getting upset.

60B1E00CB1FB4C109B2C56B1774439C3.description:
Applies different rules in contexts that
require different behaviors, such as
using indoor voices or feet instead of
outdoor voices or feet.

59D79345F0D24106B26F79B0C4E8495E.description:
Tries different strategies to complete
work or solve problems including with
other children.

2B5DC556D7884BC987E7DF6F0663AB5E.description:
48 to 60 Months: Demonstrates flexibility in thinking
and behavior without prompting at
times. Also responds consistently to
adult suggestions to show flexibility in
approaching tasks or solving problems,
such as taking turns to share toys when
many children want to use them.

5E0FD25E5CAB4A8FAF370E77EC09D20E.description:
36 to 48 Months: Demonstrates flexibility, or the ability
to switch gears, in thinking and
behavior when prompted by an adult,
such as trying a new way to climb a
structure when the first attempt does
not work.

289577A803B34F678689CB4F6C23A287.description: Child demonstrates flexibility in thinking and behavior.

8B626B6E09214FF59D8E3C3AEF1B5FFD.description:
Remembers actions to go with stories or
songs shortly after being taught.

E507DFC4CAFE4B898A1B26C1DC493B66.description:
Successfully follows detailed, multi-step
directions, sometimes with reminders.

BB011604D16D40488CC86F9574C10106.description:
Accurately recounts recent experiences
in the correct order and includes
relevant details.

556AF6E9F16A42E5AC15D8393EEDBE34.description:
48 to 60 Months: Holds an increasing amount of
information in mind in order to
successfully complete tasks.

E0729EF583494CCA98A5F7554A2E9D27.description:
36 to 48 Months: Holds small amounts of information in
mind, such as two-step directions, to
successfully complete simple tasks.

29FED79338A2447F827BC1B6D186418C.description: Child holds information in mind and manipulates it to perform tasks.

17A1D09C06934FC39945728989B72DF1.description:
Returns with focus to an activity or
project after having been away from it.

BDA9DB0CE9204CE59E0E7DC216767C78.description:
Completes tasks that are challenging or
less preferred despite frustration, either
by persisting independently or seeking
help from an adult or other child.

FD7F386796174FCABF8F697B2F2C3E33.description:
48 to 60 Months: Frequently persists on preferred
tasks. Sometimes persists on less
preferred activities with or without
adult support, such as working to
clean up an activity area.

4F3871913E4B4DDEBCC9E9202D01234E.description:
36 to 48 Months: Persists on preferred tasks when
presented with small challenges
with or without adult support, such
as continuing to try to build a tall
tower with blocks, even when some
pieces fall.

5C509F12B55A45A2B6B3E86ED8E5D259.description:
Attends to adult during large and small
group activities with minimal support.

BEEDF18CD90B46EAB5C3193D11FD17D4.description:
Engages in purposeful play for extended
periods of time.

E7B6463ED29A4B3882A8FD6A42C5CC8B.description:
Maintains focus on activities for
extended periods of time, such as 15
minutes or more.

F56D0D90BF5E428B81FDEDF8A33CA093.description:
48 to 60 Months: With increasing independence, focuses
attention on tasks and experiences
for longer periods of time, despite
interruptions or distractions.

7FCDD929D5A44DA3B636CD319AE75D83.description:
36 to 48 Months: With adult support, focuses attention
on tasks and experiences for short
periods of time, despite interruptions
or distractions.

FA53CB87F3BF4C0AABC317EAE8B2CB60.description: Child maintains focus and sustains attention with minimal adult support.

EF06FD18F2354E6D8022963FCDCA0738.description:
Refrains from responding impulsively,
such as waiting to be called on during
group discussion or requesting materials
rather than grabbing them.

87D748B4ED904D25B3CDDB5877E02259.description:
Without adult reminders, waits to
communicate information to a group.

2450D4BCB82A408A8870783A0081C3EC.description:
Delays having desires met, such as
agreeing to wait turn to start an activity.

793CB7E7E6B4441A86F6FF5FDF90FA27.description:
Stops an engaging activity to transition
to another less desirable activity with
adult guidance and support.

ED0F32B0069044C7B42E60E69A7DF3E3.description:
48 to 60 Months: Sometimes controls impulses
independently, while at other times
needs support from an adult.

E93C90C901D84AF8B80D9A1216E4AB83.description:
36 to 48 Months: Frequently engages in impulsive
behaviors, but inhibits them when
directly supported by an adult.

B2CF0EA237D747F7A93E82405CD3CFF4.description:
Begins to understand the consequences
of behavior, such as hitting leads to an
adult giving you quiet time. Can describe
the effects their behavior may have on
others, such as noticing that another
child feels sad when you hit him.

D8C1818E698C4245B0A79E5B52AB183D.description:
Refrains from aggressive behavior
towards others.

E28C3A807C44412186D062C5F29864DE.description:
Waits for turn, such as waits in line to
wash hands or waits for turn on swings.

26227671BC78477DA4EAD47655D9BBD3.description:
Manages behavior according to
expectations, such as using quiet feet
when asked or sitting on the rug during
circle time.

60379B3551204AF28ED8C8E9C16249B9.description:
Demonstrates control over actions and
words in response to a challenging
situation, such as wanting to use the
same materials as another child, or
frustration over not being able to climb
to the top of a structure. May need
support from adults.

6753FB1DD29F48C28BDEC12CBEFD1119.description:
48 to 60 Months: Manages own actions, words, and
behavior with occasional support from
adults.

30D8CBEAEB154A35B89E47C18BE576D3.description:
36 to 48 Months: Manages own actions, words and
behavior with frequent support from
adults, such as reminders to use gentle
touches and friendly words.

E6D1216BA399467F8C39FB68ED8D6E89.description: Child manages actions, words, and behavior with increasing independence.

B723E0B4ED114C74ACAF08E41C79F476.description:
Cleans up and puts materials away
appropriately, such as places blocks
back on correct shelf or places markers
in the correct bin.

3B13C6471AEB483B94A572AF06FAC268.description:
48 to 60 Months: Usually handles, takes care of, and
manages classroom materials, such as
using them in appropriate ways and
not throwing them from the sensory
table onto the floor.

BC8B73EB957B4B25B258DE24F5B73604.description:
36 to 48 Months: Handles classroom materials, such as
putting them where they belong, with
adult support.

524F14D0D8E743CA9DA2D56999810BB4.description: Child appropriately handles and takes care of classroom materials.

848DF149E8314D8484823BCD7D27F5FA.description:
Responds to signals when transitioning
from one activity to another.

32B38DCDBAA54AAC9FF77AA4170944C8.description:
Follows most classroom routines, such
as putting away backpack when entering
the room or sitting on the rug after
outside time.

4AC4625D4BD94B618FC8C9280B3B4B24.description:
Demonstrates awareness of classroom
rules when asked and is able to follow
these rules most of the time.

FB8CCAE4950D46FC876124662E4876CB.description:
48 to 60 Months: Usually follows classroom rules and
routines with occasional reminders
from adults, such as following an endof-lunch routine that includes putting
away their plate, washing hands, and
lining up at the door to go outside.

F34CF968552B4EFA8ADAD0DDD83460D2.description:
36 to 48 Months: Follows simple rules and routines
with assistance from adults, such as
hanging up their coat or sitting at the
table when asked by an adult.

9DAC28E6614142389A3BFBBD4D6D7EED.description: Child follows classroom rules and routines with increasing independence.

8A3140A97F4E4C16A05F45CAA70F054B.description:
Uses a range of coping strategies to
manage emotions with the support of
an adult, such as using words or taking
deep breaths.

94B613A96E0340798A53F89524B07F54.description:
Looks for adult assistance when
emotions are most intense.

BE8220A5C1AE41F091F759172356D4DE.description:
Expresses emotions in ways that are
appropriate to the situation.

E6B002AD90CE454585F557DC8C3F9FBF.description:
48 to 60 Months: Has an expanding range of strategies for
managing emotions, both less intense
emotions as well as those that cause
greater distress. May still look to adults
for support in managing the most intense
emotions, but shows increasing skill in
successfully using strategies suggested
by adults.

FB5614E2650A4C72B110FDB2AC7BFC57.description:
36 to 48 Months: Manages less intense emotions, such
as mild frustration, independently. May
require adult support to manage more
intense emotions.

0B42572732014E26AEB3386DB466F3C1.description: Child manages emotions with increasing independence.*
